text: I dropped out of high school when I was
17 and started doing a lot of customer
service jobs just trying to keep myself
busy and feeling pretty depressed about
life in general and somehow I got an
office job and there I met this woman
who was a programmer and she just came
said hey you should be a programmer and
I thought she was crazy and I I didn't
really think it was for me but then I
started think about it more and I
thought you know why couldn't I be a
programmer I got a job as a software
engineer and the entire time my boss was
introducing me to everybody as this is
Lisa she's here for our women in tech
initiative which made me feel you know I
felt like that just put a stigma on me
right and kind of it brought it down so
it was hard to come back from that in my
mind being a woman and you know
underrepresented in tech in general and
it kind of made me feel like am i as
good as everyone else it might feel
really hard and it might feel like a
really long path but anybody can go into
tech who wants to high tech superpower
is probably taking all of the knowledge
that I gained over these years and all
of my tech skills and actually mentoring
other people
